		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 ><a href="#p141532">Re: What is Reverse Charm Soloing and  Charm Soling ?</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=141532#p141532"><img src="./styles/prosilver/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=5955">Xleep</a></strong> &raquo; Dec 9th, '08, 07:05 </p>

			

			<div class="content">Yak put a nice list together in another thread:<br /><br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div>Charm Killing: Charm a creature, and be it's ally. You want it to kill bad guys, and don't want it to die. So you help it out.<br /><br />Charm Dueling: Charm a creature, and try to make it kill another creature at the point it reaches low HP. Then kill them both.<br /><br />All Damage is Good Damage: Charm a creature. Send it at whatever. Keep everything you can rooted. When your charm pet gets low, break charm and root it next to the other mobs. Then charm a new one. Easiest with 1 other mob, but more effective with more mobs (if you can break charm fast enough).<br /><br />Reverse Charming: Charm a creature. Gear it, haste it. Break charm and park it rooted somewhere nice. Now charm creatures you want to kill: send them at your charmed pet, slowed or on /pet hold. At low HP, break charm. Kill them with spells, or use the next charmed creature to finish them off.<br /><br />Charm Poofing: As the above, but let dead mobs poof. Useful for clearing placeholders.<br /><br />Charm Kiting: As above, but you rely on running/kiting to keep ahead of a swarm of mobs. Somethimes you use Poof, other times you break before the pet dies, depending if you want XP. This used to be a bard strategy, and it doesn't work that bad in 'gimpy' zones where you just need to clear PHers</div></blockquote><br /><br />In short I would say charm soloing is where you (and potentially a mercenary healer) Tash a potential pet to reduce its chance of breaking charm, charm it, typically haste it, give it two weapons (to make it duel wield and boost its DPS), perhaps give it a haste item (magician summoned masks work well - but and non-NODROP haste item is good) then send it in against another mob. <br /><br />Usually the target mob will out-DPS your pet since charmed mobs have anything from a 30% to 50% reduction in DPS, so you would tash/slow/stun the target to reduce its damage output. ALWAYS do at least 1 point of damage (the blue ceramic band doing 5 pts damage and a short duration DoT is great for this).. If you allow your charmed pet to do all of the damage you get something like a 20% penalty to AAXP and an 80% penalty to real XP.<br /><br />This is an extremely effective way of getting XP. Be warned though - once you get a taste for charm soloing (or any of the other flavours) you might find the XP from groups to be slooooow. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_biggrin.gif" alt=":)" title="icon_biggrin.gif" /></div>

			<div id="sig141532" class="signature"><a href="http://eq.magelo.com/profile/1387280" class="postlink"><img src="http://eq.sig.magelo.com/1387280.png" alt="Image" /></a></div>

		</div>

		
